WEBVTT

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:01.800
Round of applause for Yvonne.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:10.200
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:15.440
My presentation is titled Ripples of Change with R- It's more than just coding.

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:21.920
Imagine you drop a pebble into the pond.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:24.400
The ripple just doesn't stay in one place.

00:00:24.639 --> 00:00:28.160
It spreads in all directions, touching every corner of the pond.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:35.240
That is what happened when we introduced R to my colleagues at the Canadian Institute of Health Information, or short CIHI.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:48.160
Today, I will share how one small act of curiosity and collaboration sparked a ripple effect that transformed our team's approach to data analysis and how and why you can do the same.

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:55.080
Over the past two years, my colleagues and I moved from preparatory software to R.

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.560
As you can imagine, this journey wasn't always easy.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:04.440
And one thing that became obvious very, very quickly, it wasn't just about learning R.

00:01:04.839 --> 00:01:07.360
It wasn't just about learning a new coding language.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:11.480
It was about reimagining how we think and how we work.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.279
This story isn't just about learning R.

00:01:14.599 --> 00:01:19.080
It's about three principles that turned resistance into resilience.

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:21.559
First, start with a purpose.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:23.760
Secondly, collaborate.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:25.320
Do not compete.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.680
And thirdly, learning by doing.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.639
My name is Yvonne Kynast, and I'm a project lead with the Canadian Institute for Health Information.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:41.919
Unfortunately, I'm not able to be with you in Atlanta today in person.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.480
I'm wishing everyone a wonderful PositConf experience.

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:50.279
On a regular basis, my colleagues and I work with health care data.

00:01:51.839 --> 00:01:54.559
So let me start sharing a personal story with you all.

00:01:55.559 --> 00:01:59.919
During our transition to R, a team member was stuck on a data extraction problem.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:02.760
As I mentioned before, we work with health care data.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:06.120
And in this case, the problem was large data issue.

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:11.919
So my colleague was running out of memory because of the size, the data set my colleague was trying to query.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.080
So what did I do?

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:19.880
Instead of forcing them to learn everything from scratch, instead of telling them, I'm sorry, I can't help you.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:21.479
You need to figure this out on your own.

00:02:22.039 --> 00:02:25.559
I shared a simple R script from a similar problem I was working on.

00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:28.399
My colleague didn't need to master everything.

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:32.160
They didn't even need to understand every single line of code in my script.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:39.119
They just needed to be pointed in the right direction to use the right tool because they were at the beginning of the learning journey.

00:02:39.559 --> 00:02:44.039
They needed to have an idea of where to start and a person to turn to.

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:46.360
So I became the person.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:48.759
I became the person they could turn to.

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:56.080
I became to what I like to refer to as our R champion, and I became the bridge to our transition team within the organization.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:59.479
My colleagues weren't just struggling with R code.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:01.240
They were frustrated.

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:10.720
And I was frustrated by the gap about what I knew, how I knew the R deposit community works and how it was being received by my colleagues.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:16.119
And that is when I realized if I wanted to make R work for my team,

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:23.639
if I wanted to spread the idea of collaborative sharing and learning as a community, I couldn't wait for them to catch up.

00:03:24.039 --> 00:03:33.479
I had to be the one to help them see and learn about the power of R, the power of sharing your open source knowledge and learning as a community.

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:37.240
And this is how I became the pebble that started the first ripple.

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:50.880
Today, I want to share with all of you that everyone can be the pebble, that by starting small, sharing your knowledge and learning through projects, you and we all can turn resistance into a ripple of progress.

00:03:54.559 --> 00:03:57.679
So we were transitioning from legacy systems to open source tools.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:03.839
And when you as an organization go through such a big transformation, frustration will occur naturally.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:12.720
So when we introduced R to my colleagues, the team found overwhelmed by the endless tutorials and the internal R courses they had to take.

00:04:13.199 --> 00:04:14.800
And I could see their frustration.

00:04:15.279 --> 00:04:16.200
But there's one thing.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:21.160
If you learn an open source language, universal struggle is real.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:27.640
The sheer volume of resources you have to deal with can paralyze you and not empower.

00:04:28.399 --> 00:04:34.640
But if you don't know what you're trying to solve, the sea of options actually become a swamp.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:37.480
So where did we even start?

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:40.040
Where did our team start this journey?

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.519
So here's one thing I realized.

00:04:44.119 --> 00:04:46.359
Learning R isn't about mastering syntax.

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.440
It's about solving real problems.

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:53.279
But when you stare at your blank console, the possibilities overwhelm you.

00:04:54.799 --> 00:04:56.440
So what does your team need to do?

00:04:56.559 --> 00:04:59.000
Well, your team needs to start with a purpose.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:07.880
And in order to start with a purpose, we need to ask two really key questions before diving into any R code.

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:11.239
First, what does your team actually need?

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:13.559
And secondly, who can guide you through it?

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:17.880
So let's break this starting with a purpose down.

00:05:18.279 --> 00:05:19.600
There are three components to it.

00:05:19.959 --> 00:05:23.239
First, the first one is focus on your team needs.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:25.320
Ask the following questions.

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:26.720
Are you all new to R?

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:30.200
Do you have someone with experience in your team?

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.519
Or you are bringing in a new open source expert?

00:05:34.359 --> 00:05:36.720
What tasks do you repeat every day?

00:05:37.079 --> 00:05:40.320
Are you cleaning data, visualization trends, automating reports?

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:42.880
You need to understand what your day-to-day tasks are.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:45.160
What data sets are you working with?

00:05:45.679 --> 00:05:46.519
How big are they?

00:05:46.519 --> 00:05:47.679
And what makes them unique?

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:51.720
So the answer isn't learning everything.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.160
It's about prioritizing.

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:56.000
For the healthcare data set, we didn't need a full R course.

00:05:56.239 --> 00:05:59.600
We needed a script to handle the memory constraints we were dealing with.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.760
A quick fix that saved hours of frustration.

00:06:03.239 --> 00:06:10.079
So as I said, instead of forcing my colleague to learn R from scratch, I shared a solution tailored to the problem at hand with them.

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:13.279
And that is where the second key comes in.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.440
Find your R champion.

00:06:16.119 --> 00:06:20.320
As I stated at the beginning of this talk, I was the pebble that started the first ripple.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:29.880
And because I had prior R knowledge, I became the go-to person for my colleagues to ask questions, to help them troubleshoot error messages in R.

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:34.119
So I became what I like to refer to our R champion.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:44.799
I became the person who helped my colleagues understand the language, explain its nuances, and I also tried to encourage them to shift the mindset and think like an open source coder.

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:46.720
So here's the secret to your R champion.

00:06:47.359 --> 00:06:49.119
An R champion is your anchor.

00:06:49.359 --> 00:06:53.040
They don't just teach code, they teach how to think in R.

00:06:53.720 --> 00:06:59.799
So my recommendation for every team that is trying to start this journey, find your R champion.

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:03.799
Someone who can explain the why behind R, not just the how.

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:06.160
Your champion doesn't just write code.

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:08.079
They help you scope solutions.

00:07:08.399 --> 00:07:11.880
They will translate how to think in R to help you think in R.

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:18.200
And they will act as a translator between your team, your IT team, and any other departments within your organization.

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:21.519
But here's also one thing I learned.

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.359
Even a champion cannot guide you through this alone.

00:07:25.839 --> 00:07:34.880
You also need to shift your team's mindset from thinking of R as a tool to solve one problem to seeing it as a way to think differently.

00:07:35.279 --> 00:07:40.959
From thinking of R as a tool to solve one problem to seeing it as a way to think differently.

00:07:42.239 --> 00:07:46.839
Shifting mindset means embracing open source as a collaborative mindset.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:53.359
It's about seeing code not as a rigid script, but as a modular usable solution.

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:55.920
It's about learning from the community.

00:07:56.119 --> 00:08:01.920
It's about learning how tools like GitLab, Stack Overflow, or the interactive features in RStudio work.

00:08:02.519 --> 00:08:08.679
It's about iterating, failing, learning new methods, and actually unlearning old habits.

00:08:09.399 --> 00:08:11.920
This shift isn't about efficiency.

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:20.399
It's about fostering a culture where your team isn't just using open source tools, but thinking like an open source coder.

00:08:21.119 --> 00:08:28.399
That means asking questions, experimenting, failing, relearning, and trusting the community to help you grow.

00:08:30.359 --> 00:08:31.359
So here's my call.

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:38.599
In order to make a successful transition, don't start with the tool, start with your purpose.

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:49.039
Define your team's needs, find someone to guide you through it, and don't forget, shift mindset and let open source thinking become your team's new language.

00:08:49.559 --> 00:08:58.280
Because when you prioritize real problem over abstract learning and trust the power of collaboration, you turn frustration into progress.

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:06.559
And that brings me to my second principle, collaborate, do not compete.

00:09:07.359 --> 00:09:15.520
As I mentioned before, we work with healthcare data, and that data often contains information diagnosis codes, and those codes can change over a year.

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:20.640
Hence, if you do any trending analysis, you need to account for those coding differences.

00:09:21.239 --> 00:09:26.960
And it happened that I had to solve a problem like this, and I was asking for the code from another team.

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:34.400
Yes, the code was still in the proprietary software language, but I could still use it as a base to figure it out in R.

00:09:35.119 --> 00:09:37.760
However, I was told, no, we don't share codes.

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:42.039
But I came from an environment where I was used to sharing my codes.

00:09:42.359 --> 00:09:47.520
I was used to discussing error messages with my colleagues, and I was used to improve my codes to get it.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:52.200
So I was taken back a little bit.

00:09:53.159 --> 00:09:54.880
So why do I share this story with you?

00:09:55.640 --> 00:10:02.359
Because we need to talk about something that feels counterintuitive in a world where individual achievement often is celebrated.

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:04.599
We need to talk about collaboration.

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:08.719
Open source drives on sharing knowledge, but here's the truth.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:12.159
Most of us have spent years working in silos.

00:10:12.479 --> 00:10:19.200
We have been taught over and over to guard our codes, to guard our insights, and to not share our mistakes.

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:25.559
But what if I told you that the fastest way to solve a coding problem isn't by working alone or by working in silos?

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:34.520
So here is how you shift from fear of sharing to embracing collaboration.

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:38.719
So first, we need to teach interdependent thinking.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:46.000
We need to stop seeing knowledge as a resource to hoard and start viewing it as something to build together.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:54.200
Normalize asking questions, build the trust among each other, help each other out when you try to solve a coding problem, be brave.

00:10:54.919 --> 00:10:59.200
For me, asking for help isn't a weakness, it's a superpower.

00:10:59.479 --> 00:11:02.479
It's how we turn frustration into growth and build trust.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:06.520
But secondly, there's an action component needed.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.159
And here's what works.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:09.760
Here's what worked for our team.

00:11:10.159 --> 00:11:12.880
You need fixed exchanges or fixed learning.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:14.000
So what do I mean with that?

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:18.919
Every two weeks, we had a dedicated hour of peer-to-peer learning.

00:11:19.479 --> 00:11:22.520
During that period, you shouldn't have any other meetings scheduled.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:32.359
Just a space to walk through code, to ask questions, to troubleshoot errors, to brainstorm, for example, better ways how to visualize data.

00:11:32.599 --> 00:11:34.479
And also a space to rant.

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:37.080
Was this awkward at first?

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:38.880
Or really, it was really awkward.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:40.039
And trust was fragile.

00:11:40.479 --> 00:11:45.559
But when you create a culture where sharing isn't optional, it becomes inevitable.

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:49.960
And over time, sharing actually became the new norm for us.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:54.359
And if you don't believe it, take it from my colleague of mine.

00:11:56.119 --> 00:12:01.400
To rely on community, the fastest way to solve a coding challenge was to ask for help.

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:04.599
Even if you didn't believe it, you should ask for help.

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:07.960
And the fastest way to solve a coding challenge was to ask for help.

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:12.400
Even if you didn't get a solution, you have pointed to the right direction.

00:12:13.239 --> 00:12:14.719
And for me, this isn't just wisdom.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:21.000
It's survival and a really great example how our team learned to solve coding problems with time.

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:25.280
But I encourage you to not stop at your team.

00:12:26.039 --> 00:12:29.799
It's also really, really important to build a company like our community.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:33.440
So encourage managers to set time for the sessions.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:37.719
And let your colleagues know that you're not just coding alone.

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:39.880
You're all in this together.

00:12:40.239 --> 00:12:43.520
That you're all learning and coding together.

00:12:44.320 --> 00:12:46.599
Open source isn't about individual glory.

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:49.039
It's actually about the collective progress.

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:52.119
And when you share your knowledge, you're not losing it.

00:12:52.359 --> 00:12:53.840
You are amplifying it.

00:12:55.280 --> 00:12:56.640
So here's my challenge for you.

00:12:57.159 --> 00:12:59.080
Stop competing for recognition.

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:01.640
Stop collaborating to solve problems.

00:13:02.119 --> 00:13:06.840
Because in open source for me, the only thing we are building is each other.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:12.119
And that leads me to my last principle.

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:13.119
Learn.

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:18.080
And because a lot of issues you and your colleagues will encounter in your learning journey,

00:13:18.440 --> 00:13:23.719
it will be actually solving problems on the task at hand for your project.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.080
So my last point to successful transition to R is learning by doing.

00:13:29.559 --> 00:13:33.640
The best way to master R is through projects that matter, not just theory.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:41.000
But the struggle here is to having to learn R, having to learn a new coding language,

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:43.880
while also you have to do all the other work.

00:13:44.559 --> 00:13:49.520
And often the resistance you and your colleagues will encounter here is putting off the learning.

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:50.880
Because there is no time.

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:53.520
We had the same challenge.

00:13:54.119 --> 00:13:59.679
We were fully working on our projects, but we were also expected to finish our R conversion

00:13:59.679 --> 00:14:03.119
or to finish our R courses.

00:14:03.799 --> 00:14:07.440
And it would have been helpful if we all had even more time.

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:15.039
So how do you embrace the newly established way of thinking in R to record your projects

00:14:15.159 --> 00:14:16.400
when time is limited?

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:20.840
First, you need to realize you're learning professionally and not academically.

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:23.200
Academia teaches theory.

00:14:23.599 --> 00:14:26.119
The course you take teach you theory.

00:14:26.719 --> 00:14:30.080
But real world work demands application.

00:14:30.679 --> 00:14:36.039
When you learn R for a project, you're not just solving code.

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:38.239
You're solving a business problem.

00:14:38.359 --> 00:14:40.000
You're solving a data challenge.

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:43.080
And you're creating a workflow that matters.

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:48.440
You're creating a workflow that matters and hopefully a workflow that can be reused in the future.

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:54.039
So we talked about shifting the mindset to think like an open source coder.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.679
We also need to shift your mindset in terms of learning.

00:14:58.239 --> 00:14:59.719
You're no longer in a classroom.

00:14:59.919 --> 00:15:01.479
You're actually in a laboratory.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.719
So focus on what your project needs.

00:15:05.119 --> 00:15:08.479
Learn what you need for your day to day tasks first.

00:15:08.919 --> 00:15:10.280
No more and no less.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:16.159
Later on, once you're more confident in R coding, go and explore what else is possible.

00:15:17.679 --> 00:15:19.320
And that leads me to my second point.

00:15:19.919 --> 00:15:22.000
Practice by working on projects.

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:24.479
Here's a secret.

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:27.960
Advanced coding skills come from experience.

00:15:28.359 --> 00:15:32.799
And experience does not come from taking course after course after course.

00:15:33.679 --> 00:15:37.559
Every unanticipated error, ever data wrangling hurting,

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:40.760
treat it as a lesson because that's what it is.

00:15:40.799 --> 00:15:41.479
It's a lesson.

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:46.760
You won't master R by studying all the packages or every function within a package.

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:50.119
You will do it by coding through your projects.

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:53.359
And that leads me to my third point.

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:57.719
Allocate fixed time for learning by working on your projects.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:00.320
You need to create time to do this.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.479
So how did our team do this?

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:06.679
My managers block three hours every Friday for R learning.

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:08.799
For about a year and a half.

00:16:09.359 --> 00:16:13.599
During those times, there were no other meetings and also there shouldn't be any interruptions.

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:18.359
And to put this into perspective, that's about 10% of your time during a week.

00:16:18.919 --> 00:16:21.479
But it was enough to build muscle memory.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:26.400
So if your team, if you're on a team that goes through this journey, push for this.

00:16:26.799 --> 00:16:33.719
Protect your time because it will help you learn faster, make fewer mistakes and turn projects into progress.

00:16:34.719 --> 00:16:36.000
So here's my challenge for you.

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:42.320
Next week, block three hours, start the project and stop waiting for the perfect time.

00:16:42.799 --> 00:16:46.280
Because the only way to master R is to actually use it.

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:48.000
But let me be clear.

00:16:48.799 --> 00:16:50.799
This is not about perfection.

00:16:51.039 --> 00:16:52.719
It is about progress.

00:16:53.239 --> 00:16:59.320
Every line of code you write for your team's project is a step towards becoming an R expert.

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.599
You don't need to master every package or every function.

00:17:02.919 --> 00:17:04.959
You need to solve the problem at hand.

00:17:06.599 --> 00:17:07.439
So here's the trick.

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:09.239
Think of it like a training.

00:17:09.560 --> 00:17:13.280
You can't build muscle by watching others lift weights.

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:16.000
You actually have to lift the weights by yourself.

00:17:16.920 --> 00:17:28.079
So take those three hours, use those three hours to debug a tricky data set, automate a repetitive task or visualize data that once seemed impossible.

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:30.599
Let your mistakes be your mentors.

00:17:31.119 --> 00:17:35.319
And when you finish, celebrate the progress, not the perfection.

00:17:35.719 --> 00:17:40.400
Because in a world of open source, learning by doing isn't just a strategy.

00:17:40.439 --> 00:17:41.199
It's a mindset.

00:17:41.959 --> 00:17:46.680
And if you run into bigger issues, trust your colleagues and ask them for help.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:51.160
So let me restate what we covered today.

00:17:52.119 --> 00:17:57.959
In order to have a successful transition to R, first, you need to learn how to use R.

00:17:58.199 --> 00:17:59.319
Start with a purpose.

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:02.920
Don't let the endless possibilities of R overwhelm you.

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:08.719
Focus on your team's need, shift your mindset and find your R champion.

00:18:09.520 --> 00:18:11.280
And secondly, collaborate.

00:18:11.439 --> 00:18:12.400
Do not compete.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:20.119
Open source thrives on sharing knowledge and building bridges within your team and beyond.

00:18:22.199 --> 00:18:24.760
And third, learning by doing.

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:30.119
The best way to master R is through projects that matter, not just theory.

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:40.560
At the beginning, I shared with you that I was the person, that I was the pebble that started to advocate for R.

00:18:41.199 --> 00:18:45.680
As you can see from my story, you don't have to make a giant splash.

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:49.000
Just dare to start the ripple and be the first pebble.

00:18:49.839 --> 00:18:54.319
Maybe your team is standing at the edge of the pond today, unsure what will happen.

00:18:54.959 --> 00:19:00.079
So be the first pebble, share an idea, invite a colleague to learn together.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:04.640
Watch your single action become something bigger than you ever imagined.

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:08.520
Don't wait for someone else to start, be the spark.

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:15.160
You can be the pebble that casts the first ripple to start the R journey in your team.

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:18.800
Thank you very much.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:29.199
At this time, I want to take the opportunity to thank our analytical modernization toolkit team, our transition team, the central team at QIHAT, that made all of this possible.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:37.520
And I want to give a special shout out and thank you to our mentors, Gabriel Muniz Acevedo and Sean Salisbury.

00:19:38.239 --> 00:19:40.959
Without them, none of this would have been possible.

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:46.959
I also want to thank my manager on this project, Jennifer DeSilva, for her continued support.

00:19:46.959 --> 00:19:55.760
And I want to congratulate all my colleagues on making this transition a noteworthy success, and especially for trusting me.

00:19:57.199 --> 00:20:01.599
What you just heard was a team perspective of our transition from preparatory software to R.

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:10.719
If you all want to learn more about the organizational perspective, my colleague, Kateryna Gabanienko, will present LEND later on in this session.

00:20:11.280 --> 00:20:14.479
And if you have any questions, I'm on LEND on Discord.

00:20:14.479 --> 00:20:15.439
Thank you very much.

